<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="251" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,325,1034]" pageId="4" pageNumber="251">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,417,361,386]" pageId="4" pageNumber="251">Material studied.</emphasis>
Northeastern Europe: Kolguev Isl. (two specimens); Dolgii Isl. (
<specimenCount box="[1254,1424,361,386]" pageId="4" pageNumber="251" type="generic">14 specimens</specimenCount>
); Bolvanskaya Guba bay (
<specimenCount box="[437,598,397,422]" pageId="4" pageNumber="251" type="generic">37 specimens</specimenCount>
); Pakhancheskaya Guba bay (
<specimenCount box="[946,1108,397,422]" pageId="4" pageNumber="251" type="generic">35 specimens</specimenCount>
); Khaipudyrskaya Guba bay (two specimens); Waigach Island (two specimens); 
<collectingRegion box="[740,914,433,458]" country="Russia" name="Komi" pageId="4" pageNumber="251">Komi Republic</collectingRegion>
(four specimens); Southern island of Novaya Zemlya Archipelago (
<specimenCount box="[417,586,469,494]" pageId="4" pageNumber="251" type="generic">56 specimens</specimenCount>
). Siberia: Yamal Peninsula (seven specimens); Taimyr Peninsula (
<specimenCount pageId="4" pageNumber="251" type="generic">69 specimens</specimenCount>
), Putorana Plateau (
<specimenCount box="[494,651,505,530]" pageId="4" pageNumber="251" type="generic">13 specimens</specimenCount>
); Yenisei basin, Mirnoe [
<geoCoordinate box="[928,1043,505,530]" direction="north" orientation="latitude" pageId="4" pageNumber="251" precision="925" value="60.333332">60° 20’ N</geoCoordinate>
] (two specimens). Deposited in the author’s collection.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="251" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,325,1034]" pageId="4" pageNumber="251">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,577,602]" pageId="4" pageNumber="251">Remarks.</emphasis>
The absence of labial papilla 
<emphasis box="[650,669,578,601]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="251">C</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[684,750,577,602]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–8" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1945,1968]" captionTargetBox="[225,1367,238,1870]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[184,1411,195,1930]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–8. Schaefferia bermani sp. nov. (1–2, 5–8), S. czernovi (3) and S. cf. quinqueoculata (4): 1, dorsal chaetotaxy; 2, labial palp; 2a, labial papilla E, lateral view; 3, labial palp; 4, ibid; 5, maxillary head; 6–7, dens and mucro, different views; 8, unguis. Scales: Figs 1—0.1 mm, 2–8—0.01 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2608298/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="251">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
) together with almost complete chaetotaxy of 
<emphasis box="[1270,1287,578,601]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="251">A</emphasis>
- 
<typeStatus box="[1295,1345,578,602]" pageId="4" pageNumber="251">type</typeStatus>
permits to identify this species easily. As in 
<taxonomicName authority="Babenko, 2019" authorityName="Babenko" authorityYear="2019" box="[552,673,613,638]" class="Collembola" family="Hypogastruridae" genus="Schaefferia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Collembola" pageId="4" pageNumber="251" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bermani" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[552,673,613,638]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="251">S. bermani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[680,770,613,638]" pageId="4" pageNumber="251">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[680,770,613,638]" pageId="4" pageNumber="251" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
most of dorsal chaetae in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Martynova" authorityYear="1978" box="[1063,1186,614,637]" class="Collembola" family="Hypogastruridae" genus="Ceratophysella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Collembola" pageId="4" pageNumber="251" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="czernovi">
<emphasis box="[1063,1186,614,637]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="251">S. czernovi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are rather stout due to hyaline “cover” although this character appears to vary in regional populations. Mainly the species’ chaetotaxy is stable, with only the frequent absence of 
<emphasis box="[624,638,686,709]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="251">a</emphasis>
1 on one or both sides of 
<emphasis box="[935,980,685,710]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="251">Abd</emphasis>
.4 (in other specimens these chaetae are widely separated) and the occasional absence of microchaeta 
<emphasis box="[861,875,722,745]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="251">p</emphasis>
3 on the same tergum (asymmetrically as a rule) (
<figureCitation box="[159,227,757,782]" captionStart="FIGURES 9–10" captionStartId="4.[151,264,2001,2024]" captionTargetBox="[188,1412,1182,1882]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,1086,1980]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 9–10. Abdominal chaetotaxy: 9, Schaefferia czernovi; 10, quinqueoculata. Scale: 0.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2608300/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="251">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
) observed. There is only one exception to the morphological homogeneity of 
<emphasis box="[1110,1243,758,781]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="251">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Martynova" authorityYear="1978" box="[1110,1236,758,781]" class="Collembola" family="Hypogastruridae" genus="Ceratophysella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Collembola" pageId="4" pageNumber="251" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="czernovi">S. czernovi</taxonomicName>
;
</emphasis>
that is in several cave populations in Middle Ural Mountains. Most of the adult specimens collected in this region are characterised by the absence of 
<emphasis box="[356,370,830,853]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="251">a</emphasis>
2’ chaetae on 
<emphasis box="[528,573,829,854]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="251">Abd</emphasis>
.1–3 as well as some of 
<emphasis box="[846,866,830,853]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="251">m</emphasis>
-chaetae on the same terga, chaetae 
<emphasis box="[1272,1286,830,853]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="251">p</emphasis>
3 on 
<emphasis box="[1343,1388,829,854]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="251">Abd</emphasis>
.4 is also usually absent. Formally they could be described as a new species because 
<emphasis box="[1043,1057,866,889]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="251">a</emphasis>
2’ chaetae (= 
<emphasis box="[1210,1230,866,889]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="251">m</emphasis>
<quantity box="[1230,1273,865,890]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.08" pageId="4" pageNumber="251" unit="in" value="2.0">2 in</quantity>
<bibRefCitation author="Thibaud, J. - M. &amp; Schulz, H. - J. &amp; Gama Assalino, M. M. da" pageId="4" pageNumber="251" pagination="1 - 287" refId="ref5511" refString="Thibaud, J. - M., Schulz, H. - J. &amp; Gama Assalino, M. M. da (2004) Hypogastruridae. In: Dunger, W. (Ed.), Synopses on Palaearctic Collembola. Vol. 4. Abhandlungen und Berichte des Naturkundemuseums Gorlitz, 75 (2), 1 - 287." type="journal article" year="2004">
Thibaud 
<emphasis box="[1380,1428,865,890]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="251">et al</emphasis>
. 2004
</bibRefCitation>
&amp; 
<bibRefCitation author="Jordana, R. &amp; Baquero, E. &amp; Reboleira, S. &amp; Sendra, A." box="[247,470,901,926]" pageId="4" pageNumber="251" pagination="35 - 85" refId="ref5308" refString="Jordana, R., Baquero, E., Reboleira, S. &amp; Sendra, A. (2012) Reviews of the genera Schaefferia Absolon, 1900, Deuteraphorura Absolon, 1901, Plutomurus Yosii, 1956 and the Anurida Laboulbene, 1865 species group without eyes, with the description of four new species of cave springtails (Collembola) from Krubera-Voronya cave, Arabika Massif, Abkhazia. Terrestrial Arthropods Reviews, 5, 35 - 85. https: // doi. org / 10.1163 / 187498312 X 622430" type="journal article" year="2012">
Jordana 
<emphasis box="[344,395,901,926]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="251">et al</emphasis>
. 2012
</bibRefCitation>
) are present on 
<emphasis box="[657,702,901,926]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="251">Abd</emphasis>
. 
<quantity box="[707,783,901,926]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.08" metricValueMax="7.62" metricValueMin="2.54" pageId="4" pageNumber="251" unit="in" value="2.0" valueMax="3.0" valueMin="1.0">1–3 in</quantity>
all known congeners with 5+5 ocelli. One slightly more intensively coloured specimen (probably inhabiting upper part of the cave), collected at the same date together with several abnormal specimens, has the same chaetotaxy as true northern 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Martynova" authorityYear="1978" box="[951,1075,974,997]" class="Collembola" family="Hypogastruridae" genus="Ceratophysella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Collembola" pageId="4" pageNumber="251" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="czernovi">
<emphasis box="[951,1075,974,997]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="251">S. czernovi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Therefore, I prefer to treat this cave form as a part of the same slightly polymorphic species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<caption box="[151,1183,2001,2024]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2608300/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="251" startId="4.[151,264,2001,2024]" targetBox="[188,1412,1182,1882]" targetPageId="4">
